05518nam a22007695i 9781487596378DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191975onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875963787 a10.3138/97814875963782doi  a(DE-B1597)513855  a(OCoLC)1121054153  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD8013.C23bC63 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a331.89/041/3547100aCollective Bargaining in the Essential and Public Service Sectors :bProceedings of a conference held on 3 and 4 April 1975, organized by David Beatty through the Centre for Industrial Relations University of Toronto, chaired by John Crispo /ced. by Morley Gunderson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1975  a1 online resource (174 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroductory remarks -- tCollective bargaining in the public sector: some propositions on the cause of public employee unrest -- tCollective bargaining dynamics and the public interest sector: the market and politics -- tGovernment intervention in labour disputes in British Columbia -- tProcedures for settling public interests disputes in the essential and public sectors: a comparative view -- tConcluding remarks -- tList of participants0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Toronto, in April 1975, three Canadians and one American each presented a paper at a conference on what has become the key issue in current industrial relations – collective bargaining in the essential and public service sectors. This book presents those papers along with transcripts of the substantial and lively discussions that followed each one and involved many of the leading Canadian figures in this field. The status of government employees is one of the most prominent of the issues discussed. The speakers, Ben Aaron, University of California, Jean Boivin, Université Laval, James Matkin, Government of British Columbia, and Paul Phillips, University of Manitoba, deal with the causes of unrest in the essential and service sectors of the economy, the interrelationship of market and political forces, the results of various forms of government intervention, and also with international comparison of procedures for dispute settlement. There was a considerable diversity of opinion expressed, yet there emerged from the discussions a sense of agreement as to which policies should be followed and those that definitely should not. The debate on collective bargaining in the essential and public sectors is current in legislatures and elsewhere. This work will be helpful in advancing that debate and in encouraging the adoption of measures conducive to social harmony. It will interest students of industrial relations, all those involved in public and essential service negotiations and legislation, and members of the general public affected by the disputes and interested in their resolution. The conference was organized by David Beatty and chaired by John Crispoo, and the papers edited by Morley Gunderson, all of the University of Toronto.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCollective bargainingxGovernment employeeszCanadavCongresses. 0aLabor disputeszCanadavCongresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aAaron, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeatty, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoivin, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrispo, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunderson, Morley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatkin, James G., econtr